  "body": "  Which of the relationships below are functions? Which are not?   The relationship between the circumference of a circle and its diameter.    The relationship between people and phone numbers.    The relationship between and given by .  A relationship between and    \\toprule     3  4  5    \\midrule  0         \\bottomrule        The relationship between and given by .  A relationship between and    \\toprule     0  1  2  3    \\midrule     0  1  4  9    \\bottomrule              The relationship between the circumference of a circle and its diameter is a function. If we are given a diameter, we can determine the circumference of the correspondingly sized circle in an unambiguous way. Can you remember how? This will be answered later in this section.    The relationship between people and phone numbers is NOT a function. A given individual person can be associated with more than one phone number, such as their cell phone and their work telephone. This means that we can't view phone numbers as a function of people: one input (a person) can lead to two different outputs (phone numbers). We also can't view people as a function of phone numbers, since more than one person can be associated with a phone number, such as when a family shares a single phone at home.    The relationship between and is a function. If we view as the independent variable, there is only one value of associated to each. The reverse is also true: if we view as the independent variable, there is only one value of associated to each.     does NOT represent a function. cannot be a function of because if is the independent variable, the input corresponds to two different outputs and . Similarly, the input corresponds to two different outputs and . We also cannot view as a function of because if is the independent variable, the input corresponds to two different outputs and .      "
