  "body": " A function described in a table   Recall the table of values in . Typically, we would view as the independent variable and view as the dependent variable , meaning that is a function of , which we could write as . If we read from the table alone without any interpretation, the domain for the function is while the range is .  Now we add some context! Consider a tank in the shape of an inverted circular cone (point down) where the tank's radius is 2 feet and its depth is 4 feet. See below.   The empty conical tank. \\begin{subfigure}[H]{0.4\\textwidth} \\end{subfigure} \\hspace{.5in} \\begin{subfigure}[H]{0.4\\textwidth} \\caption{The conical tank, partially filled.} \\end{subfigure} \\caption{A tank in the shape of an inverted circular cone (point down) with radius 2 feet and depth 4 feet is being filled with water.}  Suppose that the tank is being filled with water that is entering at a constant rate of cubic feet per minute. Initially, there is no water in the tank and after each subsequent minute, there is ft more water in the tank. below summarizes the relationship between the time that has passed and the volume of the water in the tank. This is the same as , except that now represents time and represents volume in a physical context where water is being added continuously to the tank.   How time and volume change in tandem in a conical tank    \\toprule (in minutes)     3  4  5    \\midrule (in ft )  0         \\bottomrule     We can now use some of our intuition from this new context to interpret the table. In the first five minutes, the values for tell us that the tank starts at 0 ft of water (empty) and fills to ft of water. We know that the volume is increasing steadily and so contains all values between 0 and , and no values outside that range, during the time frame from to . These are significant assumptions that come from our knowledge of the physical setting of the problem! Based on this deeper interpretation, we can say that on a domain of between 0 and 5 minutes, the range for is from 0 to ft .  Exercise will have you explore this function in even greater depth (no pun intended). We will also review it during class, but if you have time you should attempt it now.   "
